Clustering on Cheese dataset

Roza Gruter

9/23/2020

Tags: #Clustering #Exercice #HAC #K-means

Introduction

Fromage dataset is a dataset containing 29 fromages and their nutritional information. The goal of this exercice is to determine groups of homogenous cheeses based on the nutritional information. IIll use two clustering algorithms: Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering (HAC) and K-means.

This exercice is taken from the teaching page of Marie Chavent (University of Bordeaux).

Given the variations of the variables standardization is necessary.

Correlations

ggpairs(dta)

There seems to be strong links between some variables. For example we have a strong positive correlation between calories and lipides, or lipides and cholesterol, or a negative correlation between calcium and folates.

Data standardization

n <- nrow(dta)
dta_standard <- as.data.frame(scale(dta, center=TRUE,scale=TRUE)*sqrt(n/(n-1))) # on va donc centrer-rduire les donnes
round(dta_standard[1:4,1:4], 2)

Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering (HAC) using Ward algorithm

d <- dist(dta_standard)
tree <- hclust(d^2/(2*n), method="ward.D")



Choosing number of classes

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
barplot(sort(tree$height, decreasing = TRUE), main="Heights of the tree")
plot(tree, hang=-1, main="HAC Ward", sub="", xlab="")

Adding dividers to decide the number of classes to keep. Judgind by the heights of the tree branches (barplot), important loss of information happens between 4 and 5 classes, so 5 is retained.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
barplot(sort(tree$height, decreasing = TRUE), main="Heights of the tree")
abline(h = 0.4, col="red")

plot(tree, hang=-1, main="HAC Ward", sub="", xlab="")
rect.hclust(tree, k=5)



Cutting the tree obtained wth hclust()

A new variable part is create to store cheeses and assignes class.

K <- 5 # number of classes
part <- cutree(tree,k=K)
head(part) %>%
  kbl(caption = "First few cheeses with assigned class", col.names = c("Assigned class"), align="l") %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 10)

Interpretation of clustering using PCA

library(FactoMineR)
part <- as.factor(part)
levels(part) <- paste("cluster ",1:K,sep="")
res <- PCA(data.frame(part, dta), quali.sup=1,graph=FALSE) # ACP norme
res$eig # bonne reprsentation sur le plan factoriel 1-2 (76% d'information retrouve)
